SIMPLE: enervate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Enervate
<hw>E*ner"vate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Enervated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Enervating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>enervatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>enervare</ets>, fr.
<ets>enervis</ets> nerveless, weak; <ets>e</ets> out + <ets>nervus</ets>
nerve. See <er>Nerve</er>.]</ety> <def>To deprive of nerve, force,
strength, or courage; to render feeble or impotent; to make effeminate;
to impair the moral powers of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man . . . <qex>enervated</qex> by licentiousness.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And rhyme began t' <qex>enervate</qex> poetry.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To weaken; enfeeble; unnerve;
debilitate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enervate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Enervate
<hw>E*ner"vate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>enervatus</ets>, p. p.]</ety> <def>Weakened; weak; without strength
of force.</def> <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>enervated</ent>⟦br⟧
